Where LLMs fit

This is where I think your observation is interesting.

LLMs are not “above mathematics” in a strict sense—they’re built on mathematical models. But they are very good at manipulating linguistic structure, which lets them work with many kinds of semantic relationships at once.

You can think of them as operating in a space where language, probability, and learned representations intersect. That makes them useful for translating between different “dialects” of knowledge:

* prose ↔ diagrams,
* code ↔ natural language,
* equations ↔ explanations,
* metaphors ↔ more formal models.

